Introduction

For my final project, I worked with 2 main sets of data (that I also joined): the first was COVID-19 data containing reports about COVID-19 in countries all over the world across a range of time, up until 10/21/20. The second was vaccine confidence data which was regarding the confidence people in different countries have in vaccines. I broke down my vaccine confidence data set into 2 data sets, leading to 3 separate data sets I could use as well as 1 large joined data set. Although I am not interested in pursuing public health or medicine as a career, exploring these data sets holds a lot of importance to me because of the relevance that the COVID-19 pandemic and peoples vaccine confidence have to my life and to our world today. I sought to explore by comparing variables across the two data sets as well as within individual data sets.

Strong Agreement with Vaccine Confidence Measures Across Countries

I began by just looking at the vaccine confidence data - I was interested in exploring the percentage of people who strongly agree with vaccine effectiveness across different countries. Because there are a lot of countries in my data, I chose a mix that I thought would be interesting - for example, I included the United States and Korea since Ive lived in both countries, and I looked up some countries with high and low vaccine confidence on the internet and included those. Some countries I just included randomly for the sake of having some geographic diversity.

This plot below shows, across different countries, the percentage of people within the country who (from a scale of strongly agree, tend to agree, tend to disagree, strongly disagree, and do not know / did not respond) strongly agree that vaccines are effective. I was surprised by how different the percentages were for each country, and I was more surprised because the percentage for the USA was not as low as I had expected given how often we hear about anti-vaxxers in the news. However, perhaps I held that expectation of proportion of Americans being higher just because of the extent of media coverage.

  filter(country %in% c("USA", "Korea", "France", "Peru", "Brazil", "China",

  select(country, vaccine_effectiveness_strongly_agree_percent) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(aes(x = country, y = vaccine_effectiveness_strongly_agree_percent), 
           na.rm = TRUE, stat = "identity")



This led me to wonder how different, if at all, these plots would look for other variables of vaccine confidence besides vaccine effectiveness. That led me to create the same plot for strong agreement with vaccine safety, vaccine importance, and vaccine compatibility with religious beliefs.

This bar graph below shows the percentage of strong agreement that vaccines are safe across different countries. There were no drastic differences, although an interesting observation is that the percentages went down in comparison to vaccine effectiveness for a lot of countries. A potential reasoning that I had for why this might be is that, speaking from personal observation, it seems as if most anti-vaxxers are against vaccines because they think they are not safe, rather than because they are not effective.

Average Agreement of Vaccine Importance Across Country from Scale of 1-4

Next, I took the scale of strongly disagree, tend to disagree, tend to agree, and strongly agree, and I assigned a number of 1 to 4, respectively. (For example, strongly disagree would be a 1.) I did this because I was curious about the average numeric level of agreement that different countries had regarding vaccine importance. I created a function to calculate this, and then used it to calculate it for many different countries. I then created a tibble to organize this with two columns: country and average vaccine importance Lastly, I used that tibble to create a bar plot showing average vaccine importance across different countries. I was surprised that they all were above 3 - I thought that there might be some countries with lower averages (which may or may not be the case for other countries I did not include here). Similar countries are still on the lower side in a relative sense as observed with the prior plots from earlier in this report, such as France and Turkey, and same with the countries on the higher side such as Argentina and Brazil. However, the difference was not as drastic as I had expected. 

wt_avg_vaccine_imp <- function(weighted_base, strongly_agree, tend_to_agree, tend_to_disagree, strongly_disagree, dont_know_no_response) {
  new_base <- weighted_base - dont_know_no_response
  ((strongly_agree * 4) + (tend_to_agree * 3) + (tend_to_disagree * 2) + (strongly_disagree * 1)) / new_base
}

afghanistan_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(2080, 1585, 413, 67, 7, 7)
korea_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(1500, 939, 486, 68, 3, 5) 
france_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(964, 341, 463, 73, 40, 47)
usa_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(1000, 628, 236, 43, 45, 48)
argentina_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(977, 933, 34, 0, 5, 1)
brazil_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(1985, 1845, 122, 8, 5, 5)
turkey_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(1027, 226, 746, 33, 4, 18)
japan_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(1157, 484, 470, 47, 7, 149)
china_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(1150, 494, 495, 142, 13, 6)
ukraine_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(492, 215, 189, 36, 24, 28)
finland_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(1127, 837, 232, 16, 6, 9)
ghana_avg_vaccine_imp <- wt_avg_vaccine_imp(995, 862, 84, 32, 8, 9)

tib_avg_vaccine_imp_by_country <- tibble(
  country = c("Afghanistan", "South Korea", "France", "USA", "Argentina",
          "Brazil", "Turkey", "Japan", "China", "Ukraine", "Finland", "Ghana"),
  avg_vaccine_importance = c(afghanistan_avg_vaccine_imp, korea_avg_vaccine_imp,
        france_avg_vaccine_imp, usa_avg_vaccine_imp, argentina_avg_vaccine_imp,
        brazil_avg_vaccine_imp, turkey_avg_vaccine_imp, japan_avg_vaccine_imp,
        china_avg_vaccine_imp, ukraine_avg_vaccine_imp, finland_avg_vaccine_imp,
        ghana_avg_vaccine_imp)
)

Different Levels of Agreement Regarding Vaccine Importance Across Countries

Next, I wanted to explore the percentage of people for each level of agreement with vaccine importance across a handful of different countries within one plot. I excluded agree and disagree since that is a separate scale. It was interesting to see how strongly the Philippines and Saudi Arabia agree with vaccine importance relative to the other countries shown. 

levels_to_exclude <- c("vaccine_importance_agree_percent", "vaccine_importance_disagree_percent")

vaccine_conf_1_data_new %>%
  filter(country %in% c("USA", "Saudi Arabia", "Philippines", "France", "Greece")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = (starts_with("vaccine_importance") & ends_with("percent")), names_to = "vaccine_imp_level", values_to = "imp_percentages") %>% 
  filter(!vaccine_imp_level %in% levels_to_exclude) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(aes(x = country, y = imp_percentages, fill = vaccine_imp_level), position = "dodge", stat = "identity")

New COVID-19 Cases Per Million Over Time and Stringency Index

Next, I created a plot demonstrating the number of new COVID-19 cases per million for the United States over time. Each point represents a day. I made the color of the points represent stringency index which is a numerical measure of how strict a countrys government was with COVID-19 precautionary measures. A higher stringency index means greater strictness. It is interesting to see the two peaks in number of new cases - the first near April, and the second around August. The most recent points are grey because the data was not available due to how recent it was (since I retrieved this data on 10/21/20.) It is also intriguing to see that the stringency index was higher with the first wave but became lower with the second wave which reached a higher record of new cases per million compared to the first wave. 

left_joined_data %>%
  filter(location == "United States") %>%
  mutate(date = mdy(date)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x = date, y = new_cases_per_million, color = stringency_index))



This made me curious about how the same plot would look for other countries, so here I tried out New Zealand - I remember reading in the news that they were successful in their efforts to fight COVID-19. The plot looks quite different - the first observation I had was that the new cases per million was much lower than that of the US. There was also one peak in April but it fell soon after. It is interesting to note that this peak was when the stringency index was highest - perhaps that was why the number of new cases per million fell quickly down. 

left_joined_data %>%
  filter(location == "New Zealand") %>%
  mutate(date = mdy(date)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x = date, y = new_cases_per_million, color = stringency_index))

Different Religions and Vaccine Compatibility with Religious Beliefs

Lastly, I used a bar graph to explore vaccine compatibility with religious beliefs (from the scale of strongly agree to strongly disagree) across different religions. I was interested to compare across various religions as opposed to countries. It was quite surprising to see Christianity did not have the lowest vaccine compatibility with religious beliefs, given that, from the anti-vaxxers I have seen in news from US media using religion to oppose vaccines, the religion has often been a branch of Christianity. However, this plot shows that Buddhism is lowest in the percentage of those who strongly agree and highest in the percentage of people who tend to disagree, which was interesting given that I had never heard of vaccinations being incompatible with Buddhism and therefore never expected Buddhists to not strongly agree. 

colnames(vaccine_conf_other)[1] <- "Categories"

levels_to_exclude_rel_beliefs <- c("vaccine_compatibility_with_religious_beliefs_agree_percent",
                            "vaccine_compatibility_with_religious_beliefs_disagree_percent",
                            "vaccine_compatibility_with_religious_beliefs_do_not_know_no_response_percent")

vaccine_conf_other %>% 
  filter(Categories %in% c("Christian", "Muslim", "Hindu", "Buddhist", "Jewish",
          "Athiest")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = (starts_with("vaccine_compatibility_with_religious_beliefs")
              & ends_with("percent")), names_to = "vaccine_rel_comp_level",
               values_to = "rel_comp_percentages") %>% 
  filter(!vaccine_rel_comp_level %in% levels_to_exclude_rel_beliefs) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(aes(x = Categories, y= rel_comp_percentages, fill = vaccine_rel_comp_level),
           position = "dodge", stat = "identity")



Conclusion

Overall, there were many surprising and unexpected findings through this exploratory data analysis. Although there is certainly further exploration that can be done with these data sets, these were some beginning insights. Through this, I was able to explore COVID-19 data as well as levels of vaccine confidence in countries all over the world, both of which are increasingly relevant to my life and the current events I hear about every day.
